biography_translated.0: Lundh, Asta Evilla, MD, licensed dentist, Stockholm. Born in Bunkeflo, Malmö county, daughter of teacher Hans L. and Hanna L. G. Married to Waldemar Samuelsson for 31 years, with one child, Kjell, born in 1932. Asta graduated from high school in Malmö in 1913, received a Bachelor of Medicine degree from Lund University in 1919, and a Doctor of Medicine degree and a dentistry license in Stockholm in 1926 and 1923, respectively. She has been practicing medicine and dentistry in Stockholm since 1926, and has been a dentist for the Stockholm people's school since 1927.
biography_translated.1: Lundh, Astor Benvard, clerk, Stockholm, born May 13th, 1894, in Väsby parish, Malmöhus county. Passed the student exam in Helsingborg in 1913, received a Bachelor's degree from Lund University in 1914, passed the oral examination in economics for a Licentiate degree in 1917. Employed as a clerk at Stockholm City Statistical Office from 1918 to 1919, clerk and temporary registrar at the Royal School Board from 1919 to 1920, temporary employee with clerk and audit authority at the Royal Board of Audit from 1920 to 1923, teacher of economics at Stockholm School for Tradesmen from 1920 to 1921, and employed with the National Insurance Institute from 1924. Accepted by the People's Education Association as a lecturer on economics and social policy. Secretary of the Board of the Psychological Club in Stockholm. Hobbies include photography and book collecting.
biography_translated.2: Lund, Bror Arvid, a clergyman from Stockholm, was born on September 25, 1891 in Stockholm to Carl Josef L., a tailor, and Josefina Vilhelmina Holmberg. He married Greta Karolina Lindström in 1919 and they had four children: Ingrid Margareta (born 1920), Kerstin Margareta (born 1921), Karin Helena (born 1923), and Anna-Greta (born 1927). Lund completed his secondary school education in Stockholm in 1910, earned a bachelor's degree in philosophy in 1914, a bachelor's degree in theology in 1919, and passed the practical theology exam in 1919, becoming a pastor in the Uppsala archdiocese in the same year. He became a curate in the Gustaf Vasa parish in 1919 and a church adjutant in the same parish in 1925. In 1939, he became a minister in the Gustaf Vasa parish and preached at the Sabbatsberg nursing and nursing home from 1925. He was a member of the church council from 1931, a member of the city council from 1942, a member of the Stockholm diocese youth council from 1943, a member of the Diaconal Board's writing committee from 1936, and chairman of the Stockholm church scout corps from 1937 to 1942. He was the chairman of the Diaconal Board's scout committee in 1942, a member of the Stockholm school board in 1942, a member of the Swedish Scout Council in 1943, and the deputy scout leader in the Swedish Scout Association in 1943. In 1943, he served as the vice-chair of the Stockholm Municipal Youth Committee and received the Swedish Scout Association's merit award.
biography_translated.3: Lund, Herman Schröder, director, Stockholm, born on April 15, 1900 in Oslo to Supreme Court lawyer Herman L. and Nina Thaulow. Married to Heddy Houge with three children: Else, born in 1931; Prits, born in 1932; and Harald, born in 1937. Received a diploma from Eidgenössische Technische Hochschule in Zurich. Worked as an engineer for Norsk Aluminium Co. from 1923 to 1929, in sales from 1929 to 1934, and as a technical director at Swedish Aluminium Comp. in Stockholm since 1934. He served as an executive director and technical manager at Swedish Aloxide Works in Stockholm since 1941.
biography_translated.4: Lundh, Klaes Victor, ship broker, Ålsten, born on August 6th, 1880 in Karlstad to provincal accountant J.W.L. and Ingeborg Backman. Married to Lily Ekwall for 16 years with two children: Mariann born in 1918, married to Tage Moberger, and Märta Klaesdotter born in 1919. Studied at H.A. High School in Karlstad and Pahlm Commercial Institute. Employed at Nordström & Thulin Shipbrokers in Stockholm since 1898 and promoted to agent in 1933. Traveled to Germany annually since 1905, Denmark in 1912 and 1914, Norway in 1926, Holland, Belgium, France, and Switzerland in 1939. Recipient of Patriotic Grand Medal.
